        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What does a local listing management tool actually do?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>It pushes one consistent set of business data — name, address, phone, hours, categories — out to dozens of online directories and data aggregators, then monitors them for changes, duplicates, and inconsistencies that could hurt local SEO.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is Yext worth the price?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yext is worth its per-location pricing if you have 25+ locations, a multi-brand portfolio, or a compliance requirement for real-time data sync across the largest publisher network. For single-location or small-chain operators, Moz Local at $14/mo covers the directories that actually matter at a fraction of the cost.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Will a listing tool replace Google Business Profile work?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. GBP is the single most important local listing and most listing platforms only sync the basics to it. Posts, photos, products, Q&amp;A, and review responses still need active operator attention or a managed service that owns the GBP itself.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do I clean up duplicate listings?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Most paid listing tools (Yext, Moz Local, BrightLocal) flag duplicates during onboarding and either suppress them automatically or open tickets with the directory. For directories outside the platform's network, the cleanup is manual — claim, merge, or request removal one by one.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is NAP consistency and why does it matter?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>NAP is Name, Address, Phone. Google uses NAP signals across directories to verify a business is real and consistent. Inconsistent NAP — different suite numbers, abbreviations, phone formats — dilutes trust and suppresses local pack rankings. Listing tools standardise NAP across the network.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Do I still need citation building if I have a listing tool?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Listing platforms cover the largest directories and data aggregators. Manual citation building (Whitespark) fills in industry-specific, geo-specific, and long-tail directories the platforms do not reach. For competitive local markets, both matter. For simple markets, the platform alone is usually enough.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can I run listing management myself?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes for one location, no for 10+. A single owner can claim GBP, Bing Places, Apple Maps, Yelp, and a handful of industry directories in an afternoon. At multi-location scale the manual approach breaks — that is where a platform like Yext, Moz Local, or a managed service like theStacc earns its keep.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

